05020nam a22006015i 9780822389156DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20092008ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223891567 a10.1515/97808223891562doi  a(DE-B1597)553905  a(OCoLC)1224277908  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aD13b.H444 2008 7aHIS0130002bisacsh04a320.542221 aHill, Christopher, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNational History and the World of Nations :bCapital, State, and the Rhetoric of History in Japan, France, and the United States /cChristopher Hill; Masao Miyoshi, Harry Harootunian, Rey Chow. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2009] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (368 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAsia-Pacific: Culture, Politics, and Society00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. National History and the Shape of the Nineteenth- Century World -- tPart I. Spaces of History -- t2. Liberal Social Imaginaries and the Interiority of History -- t3. The Nationality of Expansion -- t4. Decline, Renewal, and the Rhetoric of Will -- tPart II . Times of Crisis -- t5. The Rupture of Meiji and the New Japan -- t6. Americanization and Historical Consciousness -- t7. French Revolution, Third Republic -- tConclusion: National History and Other Worlds -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFocusing on Japan, France, and the United States, Christopher L. Hill reveals how the writing of national history in the late nineteenth century made the reshaping of the world by capitalism and the nation-state seem natural and inevitable. The three countries, occupying widely different positions in the world, faced similar ideological challenges stemming from the rapidly changing geopolitical order and from domestic political upheavals: the Meiji Restoration in Japan, the Civil War in the United States, and the establishment of the Third Republic in France. Through analysis that is both comparative and transnational, Hill shows that the representations of national history that emerged in response to these changes reflected rhetorical and narrative strategies shared across the globe.Delving into narrative histories, prose fiction, and social philosophy, Hill analyzes the rhetoric, narrative form, and intellectual genealogy of late-nineteenth-century texts that contributed to the creation of national history in each of the three countries. He discusses the global political economy of the era, the positions of the three countries in it, and the reasons that arguments about history loomed large in debates on political, economic, and social problems. Examining how the writing of national histories in the three countries addressed political transformations and the place of the nation in the world, Hill illuminates the ideological labor national history performed. Its production not only naturalized the division of the world by systems of states and markets, but also asserted the inevitability of the nationalization of human community; displaced dissent to pre-modern, pre-national pasts; and presented the subject's acceptance of a national identity as an unavoidable part of the passage from youth to adulthood.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aNationalism and historiographyzFrance. 0aNationalism and historiographyzJapan. 0aNationalism and historiographyzUnited States. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh1 aChow, Rey, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHarootunian, Harry, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMiyoshi, Masao, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle i